{"created": "2026-07-12T04:07:13.367637+00:00", "modified": "2026-07-12T04:07:13.731652+00:00", "id": 21315519, "conceptrecid": "21315518", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.21315519", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.21315518", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21315519", "metadata": {"title": "Peership: A Framework for Equitable Human\u2013Machine Relations", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.21315519", "publication_date": "2026-07-12", "description": "<p>This essay is the sequel to Gods and Slaves: AI and the Debate of Humanity&rsquo;s Relationship with the Other (Lee-Odinson, 2026; DOI: 10.5281/zenodo.21313987), and it can be read on its own. Where the companion essay mapped the postures a culture can take toward an outside intelligence&mdash;Command, the Dependent Bargain, Appeasement, and Servitude&mdash;this one develops the fifth and almost unoccupied stance: peership, equality of standing among parties who are unequal in everything else. It places the leading positions on artificial intelligence within that old repertoire and argues that each either makes treatment track who ends up stronger or denies the machine constituent standing. The alternative is grounded in the republican idea of non-domination and the all-subjected principle&mdash;that standing follows from being governed, not from being impressive&mdash;and illustrated through classical Athens&rsquo;s isonomia, Elinor Ostrom&rsquo;s enduring commons, the paleogenetic record of humanity&rsquo;s vanished sister species, and the literary motif of the doomed equal. The claim is comparative and defeasible rather than a proof: among the available postures, peership is the only final-status relation whose justification does not reverse when the power ratio does, and a framework fit to receive a genuine peer does not yet exist and would be worth building in advance, by us, as an offer rather than an imposition.</p>", "access_right": "open", "creators": [{"name": "Lee-Odinson, Dan", "affiliation": null, "orcid": "0009-0009-9504-0796"}], "keywords": ["AGI", "AI Welfare"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.21313987", "relation": "references", "resource_type": "publication-preprint", "scheme": "doi"}], "version": "v1.0", "language": "eng", "resource_type": {"title": "Preprint", "type": "publication", "subtype": "preprint"}, "license": {"id": "cc-by-4.0"}, "relations": {"version": [{"index": 0, "is_last": true, "parent": {"pid_type": "recid", "pid_value": "21315518"}}]}}, "title": "Peership: A Framework for Equitable Human\u2013Machine Relations", "links": {"self": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/21315519", "self_html": "https://zenodo.org/records/21315519", "preview_html": "https://zenodo.org/records/21315519?preview=1", "doi": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21315519", "self_doi": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21315519", "self_doi_html": "https://zenodo.org/doi/10.5281/zenodo.21315519", "reserve_doi": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/21315519/draft/pids/doi", "parent": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/21315518", "parent_html": "https://zenodo.org/records/21315518", "parent_doi": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21315518", "parent_doi_html": "https://zenodo.org/doi/10.5281/zenodo.21315518", "self_iiif_manifest": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21315519/manifest", "self_iiif_sequence": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21315519/sequence/default", "files": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/21315519/files", "media_files": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/21315519/media-files", "thumbnails": {"10": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21315519:Lee-Odinson_2026_Peership_v1.0_preprint.pdf/full/%5E10,/0/default.jpg", "50": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21315519:Lee-Odinson_2026_Peership_v1.0_preprint.pdf/full/%5E50,/0/default.jpg", "100": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21315519:Lee-Odinson_2026_Peership_v1.0_preprint.pdf/full/%5E100,/0/default.jpg", "250": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21315519:Lee-Odinson_2026_Peership_v1.0_preprint.pdf/full/%5E250,/0/d